article.headline: Barry's 3-pointer wins it at buzzer for Detroit

images.name: Stackhouse, Jerry 020307 inline
images.caption: Detroit's Jerry Stackhouse goes over Washington's Brendan Haywood for two of his 19 points.

article.linkText: Pistons, Barry send Wizards on their way
article.story:
WASHINGTON (AP) -- Jon Barry won the game with a 3-pointer at the buzzer, then celebrated by telling the heckling crowd to "Go home." Barry, open in the corner, took a pass from Damon Jones and made a 24-footer to give the Detroit Pistons a 95-92 victory over the Washington Wizards on Thursday night. "I was just telling them to drive home safely," said Barry, who went 4-for-4 and scored 13 points. "People are going to say stuff, I understand, but sometimes it gets under your skin when they start saying stuff about people's family and stuff. It gets bothersome. I'm sure my wife will be mad at me for waving goodbye to them like that, but you do things in the heat of battle that you feel dumb about tomorrow. I'll feel dumb about it, but it's over with. I don't live in the past." The Wizards play nine of their next 10 games on the road and wanted to start that brutal stretch at .500. Instead, they ended up getting swept 4-0 in the season series, and their misery was compunded by the fact that missed five shots on their final possession. "I feel so bad for our guys," coach Doug Collins said. "They absolutely played their hearts out. Detroit, for whatever reason, makes every shot against us when it counts. I think they're so confident playing against us that they feel no pressure on those shots." The Pistons set up the winning play during a timeout with 8.9 seconds remaining. They got the rebound after a frantic possession in which the Wizards went 0-for-5 -- and felt the last one should have counted because Ben Wallace might have touched the ball while it was in the cylinder. It started when Popeye Jones got the rebound after Chris Whitney missed a jumper. The Wizards called time out with 36 seconds left. Then Christian Laettner and Richard Hamilton both missed shots, and Jones had two tips. Wallace batted away the second one, but the Wizards argued it was goaltending. "Definitely it was," Whitney said. "But they didn't make the call." Collins showed a bit more restraint. "I don't want to comment on that because the only thing I'm going to do is get fined," Collins said. "I'm discouraged because the last three games in here we've had very questionable situations at the end of the game." The Wizards could also blame themselves. They had a foul to give on Detroit's final possession, but Whitney misunderstood Collins' instructions and let Jones make the play. Alexander allowed Barry, an obvious choice for an outside buzzer-beater, to get wide open. "That's all growth," Collins said. "Guys haven't played many of these games." The defeat snapped a two-game winning streak for the Wizards, who are 2-3 since Michael Jordan went on the injured list after having knee surgery. Hamilton led Washington with 24 points. Alexander had 21 points and a career-high six assists. Corliss Williamson scored 23 points and Jerry Stackhouse had 19 for the Pistons, who started the day percentage points ahead of the Milwaukee Bucks in the Central Division. Barry's basket accounted for the only points by the Pistons in the final four minutes. After being down 92-85, the Wizards tied it on Alexander's acrobatic reverse layup with 1:42 to play. Alexander was fouled on the play but missed the free throw. The Pistons used the star-a-quarter ploy. Stackhouse was the go-to guy in the first quarter with nine consecutive points, Williamson went 7-for-7 in the second and Clifford Robinson and Barry were the heroes down the stretch. Game notes
Alexander and Hamilton started the same game for the first time since the season opener. ... Collins said Jordan's rehabilitation must be going well because Jordan is getting "testy and feisty and playful." "The more feisty he gets the better he feels," Collins said. Collins, downplaying expectations for a quick Jordan return, also said Jordan had not planned to go on the six-game road trip March 13-21. "I asked him, `Will you please go? I think it's important for our guys just for you to be there,' " Collins said. Collins reiterated that he doesn't expect Jordan to play on the trip. "We'll know March 22 where we stand," Collins said. "And I don't think Michael can play before then, so we'll find out whether we can hang in without him or not." ... The Pistons placed rookie center Zeljko Rebraca on the injured list and activated forward Brian Cardinal. The orbital bone around Rebraca's right eye was broken when he was elbowed by Miami's Alonzo Mourning on Tuesday, and doctors have yet to decided whether he'll need surgery. "All I know is when he blew his nose after the game, blood came out through the hole in his head," coach Rick Carlisle said. "That may require surgery; it may not."
